  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Christian Masculinity,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2021, explores the nuances of masculinity within Christian contexts. While the book does not currently have citations or notable online mentions, it demonstrates significant commercial potential and relevance to sustainability discussions.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Christian Masculinity,\" released in 2021, provides a comprehensive examination of the concept of masculinity through a Christian lens. This scholarly work, published by Leuven University Press, marks a significant entry into theological discussions surrounding gender roles in contemporary society. Although it currently records no citations or public discourse online, several indicators suggest its relevance and potential impact within its academic sphere.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's commercial linkage is apparent, with availability on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads, indicating a broader interest among the public and potential academic audiences. This commercial aspect highlights the work's ability to reach a wider readership, which could, in time, foster discussions both in academic circles and popular discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While there are currently no metrics reflecting direct academic uptake, the inferred strength of scholarly relevance is noteworthy at 0.45. The work has introduced ideas pertinent to sustainability and policy, associating it with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals, which attests to its potential influence on future academic and societal dialogues surrounding masculinity and gender studies.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Although the absence of strong citation metrics may initially seem limiting, \"Christian Masculinity\" stands as a critical exploration that provides a foundation for further research. The ongoing need for critical discourse in the realm of religious studies and gender will likely pave the way for subsequent interest and citation as scholars continue to engage with its themes in the years to come.</p>",
